# .dockerignore — controls what Docker includes in the build context
#
# When you run `docker build`, Docker bundles everything in the build context
# directory (the `.` at the end of `docker build -t name .`) and sends it to
# the Docker daemon as a tar archive over a Unix socket.
#
# Even if a file is never referenced by any Dockerfile instruction, it is still
# sent unless excluded here. A bloated build context:
#   - Slows every single build, even when all image layers are cached
#   - Can accidentally include secrets that end up baked into the image
#   - Wastes network bandwidth in remote CI/CD pipelines
#
# This is a minimal .dockerignore for a learning module. Module 06 goes deep
# on .dockerignore — read that module for the full story.

# ── Python bytecode cache ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Python generates .pyc files at runtime; they are machine-specific and
# regenerated automatically. Never include them in an image.
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo

# ── Version control ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .git contains the full commit history of your repository.
# Including it would inflate the build context and expose your source history
# to anyone who runs `docker inspect` or extracts the image layers.
.git/
.gitignore

# ── Environment / secrets ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Never bake secrets into an image. Pass them at runtime via -e or --env-file.
*.env
.env

# ── Documentation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# notes.md is for you, the developer. The running container does not need it.
notes.md

# ── Editor / OS artifacts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
.vscode/
.idea/
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
